tasks.primingTranscript:
Session: Tracing default spectral decay behavior — no stored config case
Date: 2026-05-02

Dev: Read through LifecycleEngine.RunDecayCycle to document what happens
when useStoredConfig=true but the namespace has no stored DecayConfig.

THE COUNTERINTUITIVE DEFAULT:
When RunDecayCycle is called with useStoredConfig=true and there is NO
stored config for the namespace:
  - effectiveDecayRate, reinforcementWeight etc. fall through to the
    METHOD PARAMETER defaults (decayRate=0.1, etc.) — as expected.
  - BUT: useSpectral is set to TRUE if _diffusion is not null.

Code path (LifecycleEngine.cs, inside the useStoredConfig block):
  var config = GetDecayConfig(currentNs); // returns null — no config stored
  if (config is not null)
  {
      // ... applies stored values ...
      useSpectral = config.UseSpectralDecay && _diffusion is not null;
  }
  else
  {
      // No stored config — apply defaults.
      // Spectral diffusion is on by default whenever a kernel is available;
      // the kernel itself self-bypasses for namespaces that don't qualify,
      // so this is safe even on tiny / sparsely-linked namespaces.
      useSpectral = _diffusion is not null;  // ← ON by default if kernel exists
  }

WHAT THIS MEANS:
- If you call RunDecayCycle(ns, useStoredConfig: true) on a namespace that
  has NEVER had configure_decay called, spectral decay is ON (if the
  MemoryDiffusionKernel was injected into LifecycleEngine).
- If you call RunDecayCycle(ns, useStoredConfig: false), useSpectral stays
  false — the method-parameter path never sets it.
- To explicitly disable spectral decay for a namespace, you must call
  configure_decay with useSpectralDecay=false to create a stored config.

The kernel self-bypasses for namespaces below MinimumNodesForSpectral (32)
or MinimumEdgesForSpectral (8), so the default-on behavior is safe.
